odern notions of authorship, studies of authorial property rights have in fact lost sight of the most critical valence of owning in early modern England: that is, owning up to or taking responsibility for one's work. Greene puts forth what she calls a "paranoid theory of copyright," under which literary property rights are a means of state regulation to assign responsibility for printed works, to identify one person who will step forward and claim the work in exchange for the right to reap the benefits of the literary marketplace. Blending research from legal, historical, and literary archives and drawing on the troubled authorial careers of figures such as Roger L'Estrange, Elizabeth Cellier, Daniel Defoe, John Gay, and Alexander Pope, The Trouble with Ownership looks to the literary culture of early modern England to reveal the intimate relationship between proprietary authorship and authorial liability.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAuthorshipxHistoryx17th century. 0aAuthorshipxHistoryx18th century. 0aCopyrightzEnglandxHistoryx17th century. 0aCopyrightzEnglandxHistoryx18th century. 0aEnglish literaturex18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturexEarly modernd500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturexEarly modern. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aLiability (Law)zGreat BritainxHistoryx17th century. 0aLiability (Law)zGreat BritainxHistoryx18th century. 0aLiability (Law)zGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aLiability (Law)zGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 4aLiterature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLaw.  aLiterature.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.08iTitle is 